<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-339-565  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 339 565.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 14 1989 v3 n7 p57(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Copyright issue rocks type industry: developers fear loss ofprotection.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brower, Emily.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The US Copyright Office ruled that digitized typefaces are notprotected by current copyright law.andP;  Developers feel they are leftwithout protection for their intellectual property.andP;  The CopyrightOffice says that digitized typefaces require no originality andthe bit-mapped typefaces the programs create are not protectable.andO;The industry is threatening legal action but no firm action hasbeen organized.andP;  Type foundries continue to protect theirintellectual property through a variety of legal avenues.andP;  Thecomputer program that controls the generic digitization process iscopyrightable and typeface developers feel their fonts areprotected because they contain executable code from the masterprogram.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Copyright OfficeCopyrightFontsDesktop PublishingLegal IssuesIntellectual Property.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Copyright issue rocks type industryandM;WASHINGTON -- Last September the U.S.andP;  Copyright Office released a decisionconcerning copyrights for digitized typefaces, turning the type industry onits head.andM;Developers have said they believe that the decision, which stated thatdigitized typefaces were not protected by current copyright law, has leftthem &quot;bare&quot; -- without protection for their intellectual property.andM;But the Copyright Office contends that, from the start, digitized typefaceswere never protectable.andP;  According to the decision, the creation of digitizedtypefaces requires no originality, and the bit-mapped typefaces that theprograms create are not protectable under copyright law.andM;If the decision goes uncontested, typeface developers small and large saidthat the continued health of the industry and the quality of typeface designmay suffer.andM;&quot;Adobe and Linotype are certainly not alone in desiring artistic and digitalprotection,&quot; said Charles Bigelow of Bigelow andamp; Holmes, a type design andconsulting company in Menlo Park, Calif.andP;  &quot;Little tiny studios designingtypefaces and making digital type would like protection for themselves, too.&quot;andM;Adobe's director of typography, Summer Stone, said that some legal actionshould be taken to challenge the copyright office.andP;  &quot;The decision definitelyhas negative implications for the digital typeface industry,&quot; he commented.andM;However, such industry analysts as Andrew Seybold, publisher of AndrewSeybold's Outlook on Professional Computing, do not accept these direpredictions.andP;  &quot;When the announcements was made, there was all kinds of hairpulling,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;But from the number of typefaces I see every week, Ihaven't seen any impact at all.andP;  There is a proliferation of peopledeveloping typefaces.&quot;andM;And despite the lack of copyright protection for their fonts, type foundriescan continue to protect their intellectual property through a variety ofother legal avenues.andM;The software that turns a digitized outline font into a bit map -- the scaleror scan converter, in industry terminology, or the &quot;master computer programwhich controls the generic digitization process,&quot; in the language of theCopyright Office decision -- can be protected by copyright.andP;  Most typefacedevelopers said that their fonts are still protected by copyright becausethey contain executable code from the master program.andM;Typeface developers also trademark font names and obtain design patents forunique typefaces.andM;Despite these additional methods of protection, plans to challenge theCopyright Office decision have been loosely formed.andP;  &quot;We don't have a groupyet to formulate a policy, but there is a lot of communication in theindustry,&quot; said Diane Savage, general counsel for Adobe Systems Inc. ofMountain View, Calif.andM;The greater difficulty may be in defining what those &quot;negative implications&quot;are.andP;  Most developers said that they do not anticipate wholesale pirating oftheir typefaces.andM;Instead, the developers' concern seems to be over the perceived need forprotection.andP;  &quot;Copyright laws define permitted use of the software,&quot; explainedSavage.andP;  &quot;It is used to stop or obtain compensation when some-one is usingyour software.andP;  The status of protectability is much less clear without thatprotection.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>